[normal]Charter and Framework Agreement
[normal]2.1 In the process of the 2007 Charter Renewal, DCMS had a wide and open consultation with the industry; one 
[normal]clear message that e
[normal]merged was the
[normal] fact that t
[normal]he ability to produce high quality, innovative UK-originated content relies heavily on the ability of the people working in the UK creative media industries to have the talent, skills and capacity to deliver it. 
[normal]This meant that 
[normal]in order for the
[normal] BBC
[normal] to fulf
[normal]il its
[normal] commitment to quality
[normal] content that delivers
[normal] the best service to its audiences 
[normal]it needed to make a commitment to supporting the skills 
[normal]and talent development of
[normal] its people and of
[normal] the wider industry, especially as
[normal] the BBC was 
[normal]now 
[normal]increasing its 
[normal]commis
[normal]sioning of content 
[normal]output 
[normal]through
[normal] third parties
[normal]. 
[normal]The 
[normal]DCMS 2005 Green Paper on the Review of the BBC’s Royal Charter concluded that the BBC “plays a crucial role in training the industry and developing new technology and those
[normal] functions should be sustained”
[normal]; and continued (paragraph 7.3, page 83):
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]“
[normal]The BBC should continue to provide training on a significant scale. Its training function
[normal] 
[normal]should not be seen only as a by-product of its role as a large employer. In preparing and
[normal] 
[normal]maintaining a highly-skilled med
[normal]ia workforce, the BBC’s training programmes make a
[normal] 
[normal]significant contribution to its public purpose of stimulating creativity. We also welcome the
[normal] 
[normal]contribution the BBC makes to the development of training across the industry more widely –
[normal] 
[normal]in particular throu
[normal]gh Skillset, the sector skills council
[normal] for the audiovisual industries
[normal].”
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The Green paper also quotes from the
[normal] Neil Report on h
[normal]ow to strengthen BBC Journalism
[normal]: 
[normal]“as the largest employer of journalists in the UK, the BBC has an obligation to take the lead 
[normal]in strengthening training in craft skills and promoting debate about journalistic standards and ethics in broadcasting”.
