[normal]2.
[normal]1
[normal]2 
[normal]Cr
[normal]eative Skillset 
[normal]has an over-arching r
[normal]esearch 
[normal]programme
[normal] which involves census and workforce surveys, and employer panels whose contributions are
[normal] regularly 
[normal]surveyed and analysed to conclude on current and future
[normal] skills gaps, needs and issues. 
[normal]Access to 
[normal]training is harder for freelancers and the creative media sector has a
[normal] high proportion of freelancing, 
[normal]which is more
[normal] prevalent in those areas most closely involved in the production process. In particular in TV,
[normal] for example, there are a lot of SMEs in the 
[normal]i
[normal]ndependent production
[normal] 
[normal]which
[normal] employs the most people followed by 
[normal]terrestrial TV
[normal] 
[normal]and 
[normal]cable and satellite
[normal]. 
[normal]The SMEs are the ones that need
[normal] more support and mentoring in developing their business and their staff - o
[normal]nly 33% of TV employers have a learning and 
[normal]development plan in place
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.13
[normal] 
[normal]Diversity remains a priority for the creative media industries since content needs to reflect the more disaggregated and global marketplace. However, with just 5.4% from a BAME background, 36% women and 1% disabled the ind
[normal]ustries are well below the national employment averages. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.14 
[normal]Linked to diversity, fair access to the creative industries is also key
[normal] with around two fifths of the workforce being forced to work unpaid in order to get into the industry and many securing recruitment through informal channels. For example, 
[normal]around two fifths (38%) of the TV workforce have undertaken unpaid work within the 
[normal]Creative Media Industries (excluding an occasional charitable contribution).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.15 Across the creative media, employers have identified the following areas as important for the future of the industry:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.15 These skills issues and shortages have an impact on
[normal] the industries’ competitiveness. The recent extension of tax reliefs from Film to high-end TV, animation, games and VFX
[normal] (which the BBC is benefiting from)
[normal] has come with the realisation that the opening of such opportunities for inward investment needs to 
[normal]coincide with co-investment in skills and talent development. The HM Treasury Consultation on the tax reliefs asked the industry also to consider “
[normal]how the benefits from the tax reliefs can be utilised to invest in UK skills and talent development
[normal]”; this wa
[normal]s because 
[normal]“
[normal]t
[normal]he Government believes that investment in UK skills and talent development is a critical eleme
[normal]nt to sustaining UK production.” In our submission to the HM Treasury consultation we provided evidence of 
[normal]significant concerns that, 
[normal]“
[normal]in specific areas of 
[normal]these sectors,
[normal] the size and strength of the existing skills and talent base is insufficient to cope with the significant amount of additional production activity which is likely to be incentivised by the tax reliefs. Alongside that, th
[normal]ere is a risk that there would not be a sufficient supply of skilled people to service the additional activity, thereby leading to productions migrating elsewhere and undermining the core drivers of the tax reliefs
[normal]”
[normal]. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.16 The Government recognised these
[normal] concerns and made provisions in the current Budget for additional support for skills for these sectors, on the basis that it is matched by the industry. T
[normal]his call for industry match
[normal] is part of a wider call for the industries to consider seriously their sk
[normal]ills challenges and co-invest
[normal], particularly for the larger companies who have a supply chain of SMEs (mainly small companies) and employ freelancers
[normal].
