[normal]Overview[bold] [bold]&#xa0;
[normal]Within the Creative Skillset’s governance structure, the BBC is represented on our Board, our National Boards in Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland
[normal] and many of our relevant sector skills councils (see also above)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Anne Morrison (Director of BBC Academy) chairs our 
[normal]Digital Content and TV Strategy Group
[normal], chairs our advisory group for Hiive, a Creative Skillset new online platform for p
[normal]rofessional devel
[normal]opment, and
[normal] sits in the Creative Industries Council Skills Group; the new Director General of the BBC, Lord Tony Hall, is also one of our Patrons.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Other BBC staff are involved in other panels and task-and-finish groups which are for qualification and curr
[normal]iculum development (i.e. development of Apprenticeship Frameworks, development of Vocational Qualifications and Standards), geographical cluster groups (i.e. Bristol Anchor, MediaCityUK) and Training Provision related groups (i.e. the accreditation of HE c
[normal]ourses, apprenticeship providers and short courses groups). The BBC also actively contributes to our
[normal] research portfolio and
[normal] participates in our intelligence gathering about the skills needs of the industry. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Within our partnership work, the BBC contribute
[normal]s financially to the core budget of Creative Skillset, a
[normal]nd 
[normal]to the TV Freelance Training Fund. It also co-invests directly through providing Apprenticeships, work experience, trainee positions and internships, and short training events for Freelancers, like
[normal] 
[normal]FastTrain
[normal].
[normal] The BBC also contributes directly to training institutions like the National Film and Television School. 
